content.problemStatement:
In Java, **iterating through a two-dimensional (2D) array** allows efficient processing of all elements stored in a grid-like structure. Since a **2D array** consists of multiple rows and columns, it requires **nested loops** to access each element systematically. The **outer loop** iterates over the rows, while the **inner loop** iterates over the columns within each row.

**Syntax:**
```java
for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {  // Iterate over rows
    for (int j = 0; j < array[i].length; j++) {  // Iterate over columns
        // Access element using array[i][j]
    }
}
```
---

**Example:**
```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Step 1: Declare and Initialize a 2D array
        int[][] matrix = {
            {10, 20, 30},
            {40, 50, 60},
            {70, 80, 90}
        };

        // Step 2: Iterate through the 2D array using nested loops
        System.out.println("2D Array Elements:");
        for (int i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++) {  // Row iteration
            for (int j = 0; j < matrix[i].length; j++) {  // Column iteration
                System.out.print(matrix[i][j] + " ");
            }
            System.out.println(); // Move to the next line after printing a row
        }
    }
}
```

---

**Expected Output:**
```default
2D Array Elements:
10 20 30
40 50 60
70 80 90
```

